li.p:
g does not have a global minimum;
it is unclear
(at this point in our work)
if g increases without bound,
so we can't say for certain whether or not g has a global maximum.

We observe that

  \lim_{x \to \infty} g'(x) =\mathstrut \amp  \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{(x+4)(x-1)^2}{x-2}
  =\mathstrut \amp  \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{x^3 + 2x^2 - 7x + 4}{x-2} \cdot \frac{\frac{1}{x}}{\frac{1}{x}}
  =\mathstrut \amp  \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{x^2 + 2x - 7 + \frac{4}{x}}{1 - \frac{2}{x}}
  =\mathstrut \amp  \infty

Since g'(x) \to \infty as x \to \infty,
this tells us that g increases without bound as x \to \infty.

statement.p:
Let f be a function whose first derivative is f'(x) = 3x^4 - 9x^2.
Construct both first and second derivative sign charts for f;
fully discuss where f is increasing, decreasing, concave up, and concave down;
identify all relative extreme values;
and sketch a possible graph of f.

li.p:
f' is positive for -1 \lt x lt 1 and for x \gt 1;
f' is negative for all
x \lt -1. f has a local minimum at x = -1.

f''(x) is negative for -0.35 \lt x \lt 1;
f''(x) is positive everywhere else;
f has points of inflection at x \approx -0.35 and x = 1.

p''(x) is negative for
-1 \lt x \lt 2 and positive for all other values of x;
p has points of inflection at x = -1 and x = 2.
